IMMUNE SYSTEM RESPONSE; THERAPEUTIC RESPONSE DECREASE; FIBRIN D-DIMER ELEVATED; NEUROLOGICAL REACTION FOCUSED ON HIS FACE AND HEAD; WEIGHT LOSS; This spontaneous report received from a consumer (father) concerning his son, a 24 year old male of unspecified race and ethnicity. Initial report was processed with additional information received on 09-JUN-2021 from a consumer (mother). The patient's weighed 162 pounds and was 6 feet tall; medical history included a few previous headaches, as a young child the patient had nose bleeds and seasonal allergies. He tested allergic to mold and dust (currently very mild if at at); reported as "otherwise healthy". The patient, at age 23, received covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s (suspension for injection, route of admin, and batch number were not reported) dose was not reported, administered on 11-APR-2021 for prophylactic vaccination. No concomitant medications were reported.  The patient on Sunday evening of 11-APR-2021 after receiving the vaccine had a fever and headache. The fever resolved on the second day but the headache remained at a similar level until Wednesday 14-APR-2021 when it became vice like. He experienced nonstop facial and head pain and pressure. The patient had pain in the bridge of his nose that intensified regularly and pain radiated below his temples, around his ears and has sporadically occurred in other parts of his head. He has had pressure on both temples and elsewhere that felt like a vice although which has subsided.  His mother reported the gnawing pain was difficult for him to deal with.  The patient reported he never had experienced head pain of this type previously.  On 19-APR-2021 the patient received the following laboratory test of a complete blood count as follows: white blood cell count (WBC) (NR: 4 - 11 10*3/mm3) 4.0; red blood cell count (RBC) (NR: (4.0 - 6.2 10*6/mm) 4.72; hemoglobin (HGB) (NR 11 - 18.8 g/dl) 13.8; hematocrit (NR 33-55%) 41; mean cell volume (MCV) (NR: 80 - 100 um3) 87; mean cell hemoglobin (MCH) (NR: 26-24 pg) 29.3; mean cell hemoglobin concentration (MCHC) (NR:(31.0 - 35 g/dl) 33.6; red cell distribution width (RDW) (NR: (10 - 20 %) 12.6; platelets (PLT) (NR:(150 - 400 10*3/mm) 150. On an unspecified date, laboratory results showed the patient was negative to the Coronavirus. On 21-APR-2021 the patient received a brain magnetic resonance imagining (MRI) without contrast with results of no evidence of intracranial hemorrhage, fluid collection, or mass lesions. Mild mucoperiosteal thickening of the paranasal sinus disease. As this was the only clinical indication the physicians felt the patient had a sinus infection and treated him with two different antibiotics which had no effect. A lumbar puncture was not performed. A comprehensive metabolic panel was drawn on 06-MAY-2021 with the significant for the following elevated results: Calcium (NR:8.4 - 10.2 mg/dL) 10.3; total protein (NR: 5.9 - 8.1 g/dL) 9.2; albumin (NR:3.5 - 5.0 g/dL) 5.5. The patient received a repeat complete blood count on 06-MAY-2021 as follows: WBC (NR: 4.50 - 11.00 K/cu mm) 6.91; RBC (NR:4.50 - 5.90 M/cu mm) 5.18: HGB (NR:13.9 - 16.3 g/dL) 14.8; hematocrit (NR: 41.0 - 53.0 %) 45.1%; MCV (NR:80.0 - 100.0 fL) 97.1; MCH (NR:26.0 - 34.0 pg) 28.6; MCHC (NR:31.0 - 37.0 g/dL) 32.8; RDW (NR: 11.5 - 14.5 %) 11.9; PLT (NR:150 - 350 K/cu mm) 156; mean platelet volume (NR:9.2 - 12.7 fL) 12.4.   On 07-MAY-2021 another brain MRI was performed with and without contrast and MRI venogram which showed a normal brain MRI, no cause for headache seen, no sinus thrombosis, no hemorrhage, cerebral edema, mass or acute cortical infarction, there was opacification of the right frontal sinus and bilateral anterior ethmoid sinuses - correlate for sinusitis as a cause for headache.  The Ears, Nose and Throat (ENT) immunology specialist, ruled out a sinus infection and sent him for a CT scan which came back normal (dates unspecified). On 13-MAY-2021 the physician ordered a series of blood work: SARS-CoV-2 IgM Antibody: negative; SARS-CoV-2 IgG Antibody: negative; Fibrin D-Dimer (NR 0.00-0.49 mg/L FEU) 2.40 (Fibrin D-Dimer elevated); SARS-CoV-2 Semi-Quant Antibody (NR:<0.8 U/mL) 18.2 (therapeutic response decreased).  The physician told the patient his neutralizing antibody was very low about 31% which indicated a minimal antibody response to the vaccine. The physician felt the patient was having an immune response to the adenovirus (immune rejection of the virus which triggered a series of immune reactions and less likely to be reactions to the S protein of COVID. Gabepentin for the pain starting at 100 mg twice a day, increased to 200 mg but the dose did not affect the pain.  The physician recommended the patient receive another vaccine from a different pharmaceutical company once his current symptoms go away.  The physician would then test the patient's antibodies after a first shot to see if he requires a second.  The patient also saw an internist (date unspecified) who stated as the patient was physically a big man, he would need a higher dose of gabepentin and raised the dose to 300 mg three times a day and was later raised to 600 mg three times a day.  The ENT physician then raised gabepentin again to 900 mg three times a day; and informed the patient the pain would go away when his immune system calms down. The ENT also stated that when the patient's pain was gone maybe he should go straight to the booster shot for a vaccine to COVID 19. On an unspecified date, the patient saw a neurologist who said that the patient's events were caused by an immunological reaction to the vaccine; which caused a neurological reaction focused on his face and head.   His mother stated "the doctors who have seen him all have the belief that his head pain is a reaction to the vaccine." The mother also reported there were no clinically relevant abnormalities found in the testing. The gabepentin currently has given very little relief from the pain and pressure for the patient, which becomes worse at night. The patient was frustrated that the medications have not really worked and was afraid he won't get ever get better. He occasionally awakens headache free but after 30 minutes the symptoms were back. He has not had a pain free day in 2 months which was affecting his quality of life. No unconventional therapies have been attempted. The patient has also lost 20 pounds in the past 2 months since he received the vaccine. The action taken with covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s was not applicable. The patient had not recovered from neurological reaction focused on his face and head, immune system response and weight loss; the outcome of Fibrin D-Dimer elevated and therapeutic response decrease was unknown. This report was serious (Other Medically Important Condition).; Sender's Comments: V0: This spontaneous report received from a consumer's parents concerning their son, a 24-year-old man, who experienced "neurological reaction on face/head" and "immune system response" associated with weight loss. Medical history included a few previous headaches, and as a young child the patient had nose bleeds and seasonal allergies. No concomitant medications were reported. The evening on the same day after vaccine had a fever and headache. The fever resolved on the day 2 but the headache remained at a similar level through day 3 when it became vice-like, associated with persistent facial and head pressure, and nasal bridge pain radiating bitemporally. The patient has also lost 20 pounds since receiving vaccine. The patient underwent two magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) (without and with contrast) and a computed tomography (CT) scan to rule out blood clots. The results were negative except for findings of some thickening around the nasal area in the MRIs which led two doctors to consider a sinus infection; he was treated with two different antibiotics without relief and the Ear, Nose and Throat (ENT) immunology specialist ruled out a sinus infection. Labs showed a borderline platelet count of 150,000 and an elevated D dimer (2.4), with no anti-PF4 performed. A lumbar puncture was not performed. The physician felt there may be an allergic reaction to the Adenovirus shell of the vaccine. Gabapentin was initiated at escalating doses with very little relief. A neurologist said that the patient's events were caused by an immunological reaction to the vaccine. A physician stated the pain could be treated but the "cause" will only go away only when the patient's immune system calms down. Although there is a close temporal relationship, there is limited information to establish a definitive causal associated with vaccine. Additional information has been requested to guide further assessment.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: seizure like event; Dizzy; Her head, neck, back and legs stiffened up/her entire body stiffened; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable pharmacist. A 17-year-old female patient received BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE) via an unspecified route of administration on 27May2021 (at 17-year-old) (Batch/Lot number was not reported) at 1st dose, single for COVID-19 immunisation. The patient's medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. On Thursday 27May2021, a few minutes after the shot she started having a very small episode of seizure that lasted for maybe 1 or 2 seconds then after that she felt a little dizzy after that and then she was fine. It's described as a very brief seizure like event. Her head, neck, back and legs stiffened up and if she would have been sitting on a stool she probably would have fallen out of her seat. She was sitting in a chair that had a back to it, though, so she did not fall out of the chair. She did not every lose consciousness and he stated that this was not a syncopal event. He reported that it happened very quickly and multiple people did not even notice that it happened. Her entire body stiffened, however, "she stayed with us throughout the entire event and it only lasted a couple of seconds before her body went back to normal position, The reporter offered to call an ambulance the day of the event but the mother of the patient declined. The mother was advised to have her daughter seen by a medical provider for follow up care given the event. The mother also told the pharmacist that the patient would not be receiving the second dose and the pharmacist encouraged her to have this conversation and make that decision with the pediatrician or medical provider. Caller stated that he personally gave about 100 doses of the Pfizer BioNTech COVID-19 vaccine on that day and this was the only serious reaction that he witness. The outcome of the events was unknown.  Information on the lot/batch number has been requested.; Sender's Comments: Based from timing of occurrence, the event that occurred with the patient post vaccination which Is seizure like phenomenon cannot be totally ruled out to be not related suspected drug BNT162B2. WORSENED IMMUNE THROMBOCYTOPENIA; This spontaneous report was received from literature: Exacerbation of immune thrombocytopenia following Covid-19 vaccination. This report concerned a 60 year old male patient of unspecified race and ethnic origin. The objective of this study was prospective analysis of all of immune thrombocytopenia (ITP) patients after 12-JAN-2021 to assess the frequency of worsening ITP symptoms and exacerbation of thrombocytopenia in those who chose to receive COVID-19 vaccination. The duration period of study was between 12-JAN-2021 and 01-MAY-2021. In the study, 52 consecutive patients who received COVID-19 vaccination were identified and followed. The patients were advised to obtain platelet counts 1-7 days before and 3-14 days after vaccination and assessed for exacerbation of their thrombocytopenia and clinical signs of bleeding after vaccination.  The patient's height, and weight were not reported. The patient's past medical history included splenectomy (had multiple courses of rituximab), and concurrent conditions included immune thrombocytopenia (had since 16 years). The patient had multiple prior severe relapses every 3-5 years often lasted for months. The patient experienced severe relapse of immune thrombocytopenia when treated with meningococcal vaccine for prophylactic vaccination in past. The patient was in complete remission for 3 years. The patient's platelet count prior to vaccination was 270 X 10*9/L. The patient received covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s (suspension for injection, route of admin not reported, batch number: Unknown) 1 total, dose, start therapy date were not reported for prophylactic vaccination. The batch number was not reported and has been requested. No concomitant medications were reported.  Five days after the vaccination, the patient experienced a worsened immune thrombocytopenia. The patient had petechiae, ecchymoses, epistaxis and oral blood blisters. Five days after vaccine, platelets were 7 X 10*9/L with epistaxis. The lowest platelet count after the vaccination was 1 X 10*9/L. The patient was treated with prednisone, intravenous immunoglobulin, rituximab and romiplostim. It had been 33 days until platelet count were greater than 30 X 10*9/L. Laboratory data (dates unspecified) included: Platelet count (NR: not provided) 1 X 10*9/L, 7 X 10*9/L, greater than 30 X 10*9/L, 270 10*9/L.  The action taken with covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s was not applicable. The outcome of worsened immune thrombocytopenia was not reported. In conclusion, the results of the study suggested that some patients with ITP might have a transient exacerbation of their thrombocytopenia, some with symptoms, within 1 week of their COVID-19 vaccination. It was recommended that ITP patients should still undergo at least the initial vaccination for COVID-19.  This report was serious (Other Medically Important Condition).; Sender's Comments: V0:  This spontaneous report from a literature concerns a 60-year-old male patient of unknown ethnicity, with concurrent immune thrombocytopenia (ITP) and splenectomy, who was noted to have worsening of ITP 5 days after vaccination, with platelet count of 1 to 7x10*9/L.  Signs and symptoms reported was petechiae, ecchymoses, epistaxis, and oral blood blisters. Platelet count prior to vaccination was 270x10*9/L.  There were reported prior relapses every 3-5 years that lasted for months and one "severe" relapse after meningococcal vaccination.  Thirty-three days post vaccination the platelet count was 30x10*9/L.  No other details reported.  The event was confounded by the underlying ITP with history of relapses.  However, considering the temporal association of the decline in platelet count after vaccination, the prior exacerbation after meningococcal vaccination, and recently evolving theories in the literature about COVID infections and vaccinations, the potential vaccine contribution cannot be excluded.

Acute nerve pain in right arm, right leg, and the right side of face. Started in ball of foot and radiated up to leg, then arm, then face, then eye. Sight affected. Numbness, tingling, burning pain in right arm, right shoulder, right leg. Affected strength, walking, and every day activities.  Treatment: Meloxicam before second shot. Severe allergic reaction, so treatment stopped.  Treatment: 1800 mg Ibuprofen per day. Improved symptoms, but it did not disappear.  Treatment: 1g Solumedrol for 3 days via IV. Significantly improved symptoms, but caused steroid withdrawal syndrome for a week after. Treatment: Lyrica 25mg. Stopped usage due to side effects.  Treatment: Tramacet 37.5 mg ongoing. As pain flares, I use this.

Final diagnosis by Dr.: post-covid vaccine demyelination.

Patient is a very pleasant 38-year-old male with no significant past medical history other than a BMI of 37 and a past history of COVID-19 infection in February 2021 which was asymptomatic with  no sequela after he was required to test after his wife tested positive .he is on no medications prior to arrival, he smokes an occasional cigar and drinks alcohol only occasionally who presented to the emergency room on 6/6/21 With a chief complaint of difficulty breathing,  fever, malaise and significant left-sided chest pain that have been ongoing since May 23 slowly worsening.  He denied any recent travel any recent illness any recent sick contacts.  He denied any illicit drug use over-the-counter supplement use .patient reported he received his first Pfizer Covid vaccine on 5/17/2021 and a few days after began to feel congestion with mild coughing which progressed.  He initially thought he may be having  allergies and took some Claritin without relief.  As the week went on he developed increasing shortness of breath and cough and also developed a fever.  He went to the well now urgent care on June 3 and was told he may have pulled a muscle and was sent home.  He returned back to our emergency room in the early morning of 6/4 complaining of again of left-sided chest pain radiating into his ribs with associated shortness of breath worse with inspiration associated with coughing but no hemoptysis.  At that time he had no complaints of fever or chills.  He works at a hardware store and thought perhaps he may have strained himself lifting heavy boxes of flooring.  During that ER visit he was hypotensive and tachycardic with respirations of 30.  CTA of the chest did not show any pulmonary emboli but showed inflammatory changes in the left side in the lingula consistent with possible acute community-acquired pneumonia.  He was given Toradol and morphine and was discharged home on oral antibiotics.  His EKG at that time showed sinus tachycardia the ST segments were normal.  He was afebrile.  He returned back to the emergency room the morning of 6/5 with complaints of worsening left-sided chest pain worsening shortness of breath and worsening fatigue.  He reported any movement he develops a cough and he cannot lie flat as he develops significant chest pain which is relieved with sitting up.  He had been taking some ibuprofen with minimal improvement.  He also reported some nausea and fatigue.  He had a fever at home of 102 �F just before coming to the hospital but arrived afebrile.  Patient admitted to having COVID-19 infection in February when his wife tested positive.  He was asymptomatic other than a headache for 1 day and recovered without any incident.  In the ER he was again tachycardic but was afebrile.  His blood pressure was 137/81 his O2 sat was 97% on room air.  He however was quite tachypneic with respirations of 35 at times at rest.  Lab work revealed a white blood cell count of 13.2 with significant elevations of his erythrocyte sedimentation rate and CRP at 75 and 20.8 respectively.  Covid testing was negative.  Repeat chest imaging reveals a large left pleural effusion and atelectasis with no pulmonary edema.  CT scan of the chest revealed no pulmonary emboli but now reveals right middle lobe and bibasilar infiltrates suspicious for an infectious or inflammatory process.    EKG revealed sinus tachycardia but no ST changes were apparent.  Was clinically dehydrated with an elevated specific gravity positive nitrites but 0-9 white blood cells on urinalysis.  Troponin at 0-hour was low -3 1 hour was -3 with no change in his delta.  BNP was normal at 14 lactic acid was normal at 1.1.  Procalcitonin was normal at 0.60 and lipase was normal at 21 with a normal CMP.  He was subsequently admitted to the hospitalist service.  In the emergency room he was given Rocephin and azithromycin. The following day his condition worsened with continued fever and increasing shortness of breath. . ESR was worsened from 75 to 82 and cardiac crp now >200. A stat echo was ordered and his case was reviewed with the cardiologist. there was concern for possible myo/pericarditis so pt was started on colchicine and ibuprofen tid and the decision was made to transfer the patient to a larger tertiary care facility. stat echo showed normal ef and no sign pericardial effusion. He was transferred to another hospital where he was followed by cardiology and pulmonology. He ultimately underwent thorocentesis but the fluid reaccumulated so a chest tube/drain was placed. About one week after receiving the initial dose I began experiencing diarrhea and severe nausea multiple times a day.  This eventually worsened to begin having almost immediate severe nausea after ingestion of certain products.  It was determined that these products contained artificial or alternative sweeteners.  I was not longer able to drink diet pepsi nor certain coffee creamers due to the immediate impact of severe nausea that would also be associated with 2-3 diarrhea episodes a day.  My provider indicated he had experienced this with another patient that correlated in the time frame soon after vaccination and instructed me to quit drinking or ingesting any artificial sweeteners.  Additionally was placed on Prilosec and Zofran to consider other potential issues and treat symptoms.  Overall, inability to tolerate artificial sweeteners lasted approximately 8 weeks post second vaccination.  Diarrhea issues continued after that time frame, in which treatment with Questran was prescribed in the event that I was overproducing bile, (gallbladder removal December 2019).  Questran did resolve a majority of these issues.
HISTORY: Environmental allergies, hyperlipidemia, exercise induced asthma

I went to the hospital due to shortness of breath and extreme pressure and pain in my chest, specifically surrounding my heart, diaphram, and radiating up to my collar bones and shoulders. After blood work and EKG, they found that my EKG was irregular and I had an elevated D-DIMER blood result at 1600. I was taken for a CAT scan of my upper abdomen and they found that I had a large (650ml) pericardial effusion causing cardiac tampenade. I underwent a procedure that inserted a needle into my pericardium, sucked out the fluid, and inserted a drain tube for 48 hours to drain excess fluid. Upon additional testing, it was determined that I had none of the usual causes for a pericardial effusion (no heart attack or trauma, no infection either viral or bacterial, no cancer, no autoimmune conditions.) My inflammation markers were extremely elevated and my lymph nodes in CAT scan were swollen. As a result, I now have constrictive pericarditis, scar like tissue surrounding my heart constricting its function.

I woke up in the night about a week after the first vaccine (around 4:00 AM on 04/07/2021) having trouble breathing -- tight throat and chest. I thought it was my sinus infection, received a negative covid test, and started taking augmentin. The tightness continued for about 3 days along with a shortness of breath, no other symptoms though. My resting heart rate was also hovering around 100 bpm until the weekend before the second vaccine.  I had no initial reaction to the second vaccine either. However, about a week later the same thing happened. I woke up around 1:00 AM 04/26/2021 hyperventilating with a tight throat and chest. This continued for about 3 days again, so I took another covid test -- negative again. My resting heart rate was back up to 100 bpm. I started to think it was a strange reaction to the vaccine, so I still had my infusion for Crohn's Disease on 04/30/2021. Blood pressure was okay, somewhere around 104/67 I think, but my heart rate was 107 bpm. After that weekend, I felt back to normal. Not sure if this was all caused by the vaccines, but it seems possible.

a 52 y.o. male sent for evaluation due to symptoms which have now lasted for months and began occurring shortly after he received his second Materna vaccine.  He had his first Madrona vaccine on 3/26/2021, and his second vaccine on 4/23/2021.  Initially he noted headaches, neuralgia, chills and sweats, and just suspected these would dissipate as had been described in the media.  His headaches and neuralgia did resolve, but he continued to have significant night sweats and fatigue.  He had one episode where he passed out and struck his head.  This has not recurred for over a month.  He has had 2 episodes of vomiting bilious material these were significantly spread out.  He has noted a 20 pound weight loss and difficulty sleeping.  He does report that in the last few days his symptoms seem to have improved, and his appetite has improved as well, but he has not noticed any weight gain yet.  He did have low-grade fevers the highest being in the 101 range.  He had no visual, taste, pulmonary, genitourinary, rheumatological, or dermatological complaints.  Apart from the 2 episodes of vomiting he has had no GI issues.  His wife is present and concurs with his history.  He has had a significant work-up from his primary care provider who included an LDH in late May that was normal, CBC with differential which was benign, a Monospot which was negative, CRP that was elevated at 85 with 0-10 being the reference range, a negative ANA, negative RA, and a sedimentation rate of 42, blood cultures were performed and were negative.  Labs earlier in the month noted similar findings.  His basic metabolic panel and liver enzymes were also normal.  He was also reportedly screened for Lyme and was negative but I do not see this test result.   He denies any childhood infections of significance. The also went to a safari in 2019.  They traveled recently prior to the onset of his symptoms but he reports no known bites or scratches by ticks, insects, mosquitoes, or other animals.  No one else in the household has been sick.  He did receive the BCG vaccine as a child.  They also report a chest x-ray was performed and was benign.  He was given a 10-day course of amoxicillin and reports no significant improvement while on this.

I received both of my COVID-19 vaccines.  Both of these vaccines were the Pfizer vaccinations. My first shot was given on 3/9/21 and my 2nd shot was given on 3/30/21. About 2 1/2 weeks after I received my 2nd shot I began to feel a  lot of pressure in my chest.  It felt like an elephant was sitting on my chest.  After feeling this extreme discomfort for a few days I began to get worried and decided to go to the Emergency Room to get it checked out.  I went to a hospital. They administered an EKG, took a chest x-ray and drew my blood.   The physician on duty looked at the chest x-ray and told me that my heart wasn't enlarged. He also said it looks like I hadn't had a heart attack.   I suppose my EKG came out normal since they didn't seem alarmed at those results.  My blood panel showed I was a bit low in sodium but otherwise everything was normal.  The next day I felt normal again and haven't felt the chest pressure since. I blame the Pfizer COVID-19 vaccines for having that feeling of extreme pressure on my chest for several days.  I'm a bit concerned about receiving any future COVID vaccinations from this result not knowing if the next vaccination might cause a heart attack.
LAB_DATA: Emergency Room where they gave me an EKG, a chest x-ray and  drew my blood.

Shortly after 1st Moderna shot on Mar 2 2021 I had what I thought was an asthma exacerbation. When breathing did not improve with previously prescribed rescue inhaler and daily oral medication, I saw my primary on Mar 26, 2021.  My primary gave me a  nebulizer treatment, prescribed a z-pack and renewed my Albuteral rescue inhaler. I got no relief from those interventions. On Mar 30, 2021 I had my 2nd Moderna vaccination. I walk daily, usually fast paced with moderate-high exertion, but while having difficulty breathing I  walked slowly with light exertion. On Apr 2nd I was on my walk, short of breath, when I experienced pain in my left chest which moved into my left arm. My left arm was tingling then numb. I stopped and rested until the pain went away, maybe 3-4 minutes. I continued walking  back to the car. My arm remained tingling and numb during that time and for about 30 minutes.  I never felt the same level of pain that I did on April 2nd, but I continued to have shortness of breath, felt twinges/pinches and sometime a quick stab in my left chest. I also had some tightness/pressure in my left neck/throat. My blood pressure was also higher than normal for me. I have had a couple of asthma attacks in my life, but my asthma has been well-controlled and any breathing issues were always able to be resolved with my acute inhaler and a Nebulizer treatment. I had never had chest pain. I saw my primary at a first available appointment who set me up with appointments for pulmonary and cardiology. During this period I also was prescribed additional medications; 1 baby aspirin/day; Symbicort; Metoprolol; nitro (if needed for chest pain). My breathing got worse with the Metoproplol after 5 days and I was given Amlodipine instead. My breathing got easier with the change in medication. I found that lying down on my side helped my breathing. I have not been wakened by not being able to breathe during sleep and feel good first thing in the morning. Once I start moving around in the morning I feel shortness of breath during normal activity. Some days are  improved, some days aren't as good. I have been avoiding even moderate exertion so I don't know if I would have chest pain like I experienced on Apr 2nd again. In addition to the shortness of breath I still feel a twinge/pinch in my left chest and a tightness/pressure on my left neck/throat area. My cardio cath Left/Right was performed Jun 14, 2021. There was no sign of any issues with my heart and no sign of pulmonary hypertension. As of this submission on  Jun 15, 2021, I am grateful that there are no problems or concerns with my heart or lungs. I'll follow my doctor's orders to increase exercise and will have a Pulmonary Function Test in July. I was a person who went from being able to walk 3 miles at a fast pace with 100 foot elevation changes within 1/4 mile to having difficulty walking from my kitchen to the bathroom in a matter of weeks. The only anomaly in that time frame was my 2 Moderna vaccine shots. I'm submitting this because I feel you should know and because I am concerned with what I should do if a booster is required in the future.
LAB_DATA: chest xray (Apr 28), EKG (May 12), Echo-cardiogram & Stress Test (May 27), CT Chest (Jun 7), Covid Test (Jun 11), Cardio Cath Right & Left (Jun 14), several lab/blood draws. Results from all procedures and labs were normal with nothing indicating an issue, the covid test was negative.

Patient received vaccine series at a separate facility. I do not have access to this information. He reported receiving Moderna dose #2 on Tuesday, June 8. Within hours, he began to have chest pain, shortness of breath, general body aches and fatigue. Chest pain was worse with deep breath and worse with supine position.  On Friday, June 11, he presented to The Clinic at  with these complaints. He was noted to be in evident severe discomfort, though not in respiratory distress. Vitals as follows: pulse 82 and regular, BP 139/68, respiratory rate 20, temperature 99.2 oral, SaO2 98% on room air. Exam was notable for absence of a pericardial friction rub. Lungs were clear to auscultation. he had no rashes and no remarkable tenderness of the body to palpation. Extremities were without edema. There was no sign of clinical heart failure or cardiovascular insufficiency.
LAB_DATA: Electrocardiogram showed diffuse ST segment elevation, felt consistent with acute pericarditis. chest radiographs were normal. Serum troponin level was markedly elevated at >30 ng/ml, too high to be accurately measured with our instrumentation. Erythrocyte sedimentation rate elevated at 25 mm/hr (nl range 0-10).  C reactive protein elevated at 7.84 mg/dL (nl range 0.00-0.90). Complete blood count normal. Covid-19 nucleic acid amplification test by nasal swab negative.  I consulted with cardiology by phone. Patient was advised to seek emergency department care for urgent echocardiogram, repeat troponin level, and observation. In the approximately one hour the patient was in our facility, his symptoms improved considerably, without treatment.
HISTORY: HIstory of depressive disorder, currently in remission

On 6/11/2021, patient presented to the Emergency Department complaining of chest pain that started initially in the evening of 6/10, which had initially self-resolved, but has since recurred, now also with shortness of breath.  Troponin was significantly elevated on presentation at 16.3, and 12-lead EKG showed an abnormal rhythm concerning for STEMI vs perimyocarditis.  After negative cardiac/embolic work-up in cath lab & CT imaging, myocarditis was felt to be the most likely cause of this patient's symptoms.  On the following day, patient was noted to have brief bursts of Vtach, for which metoprolol was initiated.  The patient was subsequently discharged home in stable condition on 6/13/2021.
LAB_DATA: Chemistry panel + troponin (6/11/2021, 6/12/2021), 12-lead EKG (6/11/2021), Coronary catheterization (6/11/2021), CT angiogram (6/11/2021).

Since receiving my second dose of the modern COVID vaccine, but I believe it started after my first, I have had a pretty severe hormonal disruption. I have gained 6 lbs and have had severe hormonal cystic acne breakouts on my chin that I have NEVER had to this degree or this long (going on two months). This happened almost instantly after my second dose. There have been no other factors in my life that have changed. My uterus had previously been surgically removed, but I have my ovaries. I can't comment on a disruption to a menstrual cycle because that does not affect me. The hormonal imbalance has most definitely affected my daily life and I am now on a strong topical prescription to try and get the acne under control. This is not life threatening but very concerning.

Tachycardia x 2+ months 3 trips to the ED, 30 day heart rate monitor followed by cardiology.  Echocardiogram.  March 9th I was driving with my 7 year old in the car and had to pull over and call 911.  First month symptoms were dizzyness and shortness of breath, tachycardia and chest pain.  I went from being a healthy runner/weight training to no working out.  I cut coffee and caffeine and kept a food diary to see if anything helped, nothing did.  At month two tachycardia slowed and is now more regulated.  My current  symptoms remainining are chest pain/pressure.  Cardiology believes this is inflammation post vaccine, as my overall cardiac workup was healthy.  Cardiac MRI is an option.  No medication was given.  I have completely changed my diet to anti inflammatory, changed my workouts to yoga, and am dealing with residual symptoms that have altered my life.

No adverse effect. Patient was given by mistake, the second dose of different COVID vaccine Manufacturer.  Patient was observed for a total of 40 minutes after the vaccine was administered. No s/e observed.  We contacted manufacturer. for information in regards adverse effects and recommendation to continue with series.  Spoke with the Medical information department. Immediately after the shot, my shoulder became very painful. I noticed that the band-aid from the injection was located very high on my arm, right at the shoulder joint towards the back. My arm stayed painful, and I couldn't sleep. I couldn't move my arm normally. I read that arm pain was a normal side effect, so I waited. After 7-8 days, on April 3, I went to the urgent care for a virtual visit. I was seen by a PA. She had my husband rotate my arm in several ways, and it would move normally except if directly out to the side and up over my head. I couldn't raise my arm past horizontal, and my shoulder was very painful. She recommended Ibuprofen, ice, and movement. I did those things, but my arm still was not able to move normally. It felt stuck when I tried to raise it. I went in on April 30 for an in-person visit with my doctor. She examined my shoulder and recommended physical therapy and that I see an orthopedist. I had some difficulty getting authorizations in place in a timely manner, and eventually was able to see an orthopedist for a virtual visit on June 1. He recommended physical therapy and to call back for an MRI if it doesn't resolve after 6 weeks. I had my first physical therapy appointment with  a clinic on June 8. I am currently doing daily PT and seeing the PT weekly.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 24yo  female with anovulatory vaginal bleeding and cramping x5 days which presented within 24 hours of receiving her 2nd dose Moderna COVID-19 vaccination on 06/09/2021. Patient describes her symptoms as if she is having a normal menstrual cycle.  This patient uses Nexplanon for contraception successfully without a menstrual cycle for the past 2 years.  Denies other urinary or vaginal symptoms, or possibility that she may be pregnant.  Although there is high suspicion that this is a COVID-19 vaccine side effect, I will evaluate for abnormal anovulatory uterine bleeding with labs and follow-up with ulatrasound if her symptoms do not resolve with time.    24yo female with left sided supraclavicular lymphadenopathy presenting within 24hrs of her 1st and 2nd dose of the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine.  Patient endorses waning symptoms after the first dose until she received the second dose at which point the lymph node came back.  Physical exam remarkable for one 1x1cm left sided supraclavicular lymph node tender to palpation.  Likely reactive lymphadenopathy.  I will treat with watchful waiting given reactive lymphadenopathy to include supraclavicular lymphadenopathy is a known side effect of the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine, and that patient's young age and lack of risk factors.  If persistent over several months I will re-evaluate the lymph node with imaging.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Starting on the day after the vaccine 2nd dose, I got a very bad severe migraine like  headache right away.   I had extreme sensitivity to light and had to lay down.  My left eye was getting blurry and I was feeling severe pressure and pain.  I could not walk or stand up and felt very heavy.  I had tinnitus (ringing in both ears) and painful  inner ear pressure that exacerbated my headaches.  The next day, my symptoms were getting worse and now I had pain in my neck and spine. My joints in my spine and neck felt swollen,inflamed and was very painful.  I called my PCP and they recommended Tylenol and to  go to Urgent Care.  I was prescribed Prednisone and muscle relaxer.  The medications did not help.  My PCP then advised to go to the ER.  They did blood work, 2 spinal taps, MRI and CAT scan.  I was in the hospital for 1 night.  Everything came back normal.  I was discharge and instructed to let the vaccine run its course.   I am still suffering with nausea, headaches, pain in neck and spine with no improvements. It has affected my quality of life and I am still out of work.  I am unable to do simple daily tasks.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 02/25/2021: Patient received 1st dose of Moderna 03/17 ? 3/19: 20 days after 1st dose, c/o progressively worsening bilateral lower extremity weakness of several weeks? duration. Patient had also suffered from recurrent falls over the preceding several days prior to admission. subsequent CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis revealed severe hepatic steatosis and a CT angiogram of the chest revealed bilateral pulmonary emboli. She subsequently had a duplex ultrasound of the lower extremities that revealed a right lower extremity DVT. MRI of the lumbar spine was performed for further evaluation of her bilateral lower extremity weakness that revealed some moderate bilateral neuroforaminal narrowing with mild spinal stenosis at L3-L4 and moderate spinal stenosis at L4-L5 with some degenerative endplate changes at similar levels. Dx: Pulmonary embolism - discharged home on Xarelto for complete treatment of her DVT/PE. 3/25: 2nd dose of Moderna given at Primary care - referred to ER for complaints. 3/25: ER encounter - She has been experiencing heavy vaginal bleeding, passing large clots at times, for the past six days. She reports that she usually has regular menstrual cycles, regulated on oral contraceptive pills. Dx: Menorrhagia with regular cycle, Anticoagulated ? treated and discharged on TXA 3/28 ? 4/4: 3 days after 2nd dose. presents with ongoing vaginal bleeding complicated by lightheadedness with standing, generalized weakness and fatigue, and dyspnea on exertion. Patient states she has been bleeding for almost 2 weeks vaginally. Dx: severe symptomatic anemia due to dysfunctional uterine bleeding / Menorrhagia and need for anticoagulation, Folate deficiency anemia, Venous stasis. Rx: Transfused 3 units, Provera, Due to recent VTE in stable hemoglobin cautiously started heparin, Oral contraceptives stopped, resumed Xarelto, folic acid supplement.

57 y.o. female with PMH significant for multiple comorbidities including history of obstructive sleep apnea, chronic left shoulder pain s/p surgery in the past, right carpal tunnel surgery recently, came into the ER from home with complaint of shortness of breath.  Patient was in her usual state of health at least until last Tuesday when she got her second Covid shot, starting Wednesday she started to have pleuritic chest pain, followed by shortness of breath.  Shortness of breath progressively was getting worse, increased on exertion, subsequently was short of breath at rest and even on talking.  Patient also noted frothy sputum tinged with blood.  Secondary to above patient initially had a televisit with PCP early this morning and was instructed to come to ED. On further questioning patient denies complains of associated nausea, vomiting, diarrhea abdominal pain.  Denies any fever, chills. Denies any other complaints of melena or hematochezia  In the ED further work-up including a CT angio pulmonary showed evidence of PE.  pt was treated and discharged the next day on Xarelto.  On 6/13/21, pt presented back to ED with Chest heaviness and shortness of breath  for 3 days Patient with recent diagnosis of unexplained pulmonary embolism. She was loaded with Xarelto for 21 days and subsequently is taking the full daily dose now. Ultrasound of legs was not performed to her initial hospitalization. CTA was repeated today and does not show new pulmonary emboli. CTA on May 17 showed small pulmonary emboli in the lobular in segment mental left lower lobe pulmonary arteries as well as a segmental right middle lobe and lingular pulmonary arteries. She had a left pleural effusion. This was later tapped. Cardiac echo obtained on 518 showed a small pericardial effusion. LVEF at that time was normal. RV systolic pressure was estimated at 36 mmHg. This is only slightly elevated. The patient is normally very active and wanted to get back to her normal activities. On Thursday she did some exercise and subsequent developed her current symptoms of chest heaviness and shortness of breath. She backed off on the exercise. She now came to the emergency room. Troponin is negative. EKG has nonspecific changes. Repeat CTA is now not showing pulmonary embolism. There is no significant pericardial effusion or pleural effusion seen. No evidence of recurrent pulmonary emboli and pt was discharged home.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt with no PMH. Was administered IM vaccine at approximately 08:45. Within 5 minutes endorsed feeling dizzy, appeared pale and slightly diaphoretic. Pt had witnessed syncopal episode at approximately 08:50. Pt seated with nurse and site employees at side to assist in ensuring safety. No injury occurred. Syncopal episode duration approximately 30 seconds. Pt became unresponsive, bradycardic and slightly hypotensive. Vitals: 110/55, 50, 13, 98%. EMS activated, PD called, and Capt called to be made aware of situation. Pt given Gatorade 150 ml and endorsed prior syncopal episodes with vaccines and blood draws. 8:53- Pt able to sit upright independently, drink fluids w/ no complication, AAO x4. Pt vital signs stabilized within 5 minutes with no other interventions other than PO fluids. PD arrived onsite 8:56, asked pt if he required medical assistance, pt declined. PD officer given report by lead RN. RA 51 arrived 8:58, report given by lead RN, pt evaluated, performed EKG finding NSR, and fingerstick glucose result of 163. 09:00- pt reports dizziness resolved, and declined transport to hospital by PD and signed AMA. 09:45 pt remained continuously monitored by site RNs, along with PD assessment. Pt exited site ambulatory with no further incidents accompanied by wife.
LAB_DATA: EKG performed by PD with NSR Finger stick blood glucose performed by PD with result 163 Vital signs at departure 130/75, 70, 13, 99%
PRIOR_VAX: syncope, unknown dates

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Initially I just had the tiredness for a couple of days and muscle aches and chills at night and then things seemed to get better. Then sometime in February I became very "spacey", it was hard to remember things that I usually readily knew. I could be talking and forget what I was saying, I am a mental health therapist and I have always been able to remember things that now I cannot recall things that happen the days before. I have a lot of trouble remembering day to day things - very forgetful. Don't seem to retain information well anymore. Slow cognitive functioning that lasted through April and then in May I started recognizing/feeling like it lifted. That fog was gone and I still feel a little spacey every now and then but it is not anything like it was before. I went to my DR about it and she prescribed for me (mid May) supplements that have helped with my energy. I am a very active person normally and I had no energy during this whole time. The fatigue and mental fog were the big things that I experienced. The supplements that she game me were medical grade multivitamin, B vitamins and some other things. With those I have gotten to pretty much normal. My friend that got the same vaccine as me experienced the same exact symptoms and process so I hope that is helpful as well. It lasted about three months for me.
LAB_DATA: Extensive blood work to see all levels and discovered very low b12 and vitamin d and little low on thyroid

Mild to moderate tinnitus in both ears. Started approx the day after receiving first dose. More noticeable when less background noise. Hear it every day. Not really any changes in symptoms. Within the first two weeks however, I heard occasional and much louder and noticeable bursts of ear ringing that lasted 15-30 seconds. Have not heard that since the first couple of weeks. Now just chronic mild tinnitus, which is currently manageable. I would very much like to get fully vaccinated, but I'm very concerned about receiving the second dose since others I've spoken to who have experienced similar side effects from the first dose have reported worsening on second dose and some indicating their tinnitus becoming unmanageable. I'm very concerned that this condition could become disabling after second dose. I've tried very hard to research this and see if there are any mitigation measures that I could do to prevent worsening of tinnitus on second dose. Only thing I have heard is that I should receive second dose as far as possible from area of side effect, and that my second shot should be in the thigh. I also considered getting one of the other vaccines as the second dose, but they have all had reports of tinnitus, so I don't think that would make a difference. The general medical community has no knowledge of how to help people with this issue and is not accepting that my condition was caused by the vaccine. However, I have NEVER had long term tinnitus. Only rarely in my life, which was short lived, such as after hearing a loud noise. But not like this. While the medical community can debate the cause and effect, I'm fairly confident my reaction was due to the vaccine. People who have Covid also have reported tinnitus, so I imagine this is something to do with the body's immune response. There are MANY more people experiencing this side effect than have reported I am sure. These people would all like to be fully vaccinated (if they have not received the second dose) and this needs to be addressed if we are going to help relieve their hesitancy. The Director for a large regional hospital system in the area told me that my choice is: receiving the second dose and possibly becoming disabled with severe Tinnitus (as side effects experienced on first dose are normally, but not always, worse after second dose of a vaccine) OR getting Covid!!Neither one is a good outcome!!
OTHER_MEDS: Prozac (10 mg/dy); multivitamin; Vit D 3,000 IU/day (4,000 IU total Vit D including multi vitamin supplement), melatonin at 5 mg prior to bedtime (approx 2 times per week)
CUR_ILL: None. Occasional seasonal allergies, minor and controllable with Zyrtec, etc

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Developed bilateral erythromelalgia on the palms of hands. Extreme redness, tingling and pain. Initial reaction 4 days after the shot was extremely painful. She said to give it two more weeks and then she'd prescribe a steroid cream. I touched base with my primary care doctor when I was 6 wks out from shot and I was still having this reaction. She had me see a rheumatologist to see if I had an underlying autoimmune disorder that we didn't know about and that was what got triggered by vaccine. The rheumatologist did an autoimmune workup and nothing was found. She is the one that used the term erythromelagia and suggested that if the pain was not tolerable when the tingling happened that I could see a neurologist. The reaction still happens. It is primarily associated with heat, physical activity/manipulations with my hands or with stress. I never had this before and came on so suddenly on the morning of the 4th day after my shot.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient is a 15-year-old male with no past medical history who was in his normal state of health when he received a dose to the Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine on June 10th 2021. The day following vaccine he developed fevers and chills which she treated with Tylenol.  On the morning of June 12 he developed chest pain and nausea which progressively worsened throughout the day.  That day he presented to an outside hospital emergency department where he was found to have elevated troponin and EKG with ST segment elevation.  He was then transferred to the hospital pediatric ICU for further care.  On admission to the PICU treatment was started with IV Toradol.  Echocardiogram was performed and revealed mildly decreased left ventricular systolic function.  His peak troponin level was 27.43.  He remains hemodynamically stable and was transferred to the pediatric floor.  By 6/14/2021 his chest pain had resolved and he continued to improve with NSAID therapy alone.  His troponin down trended to 2.62 on day of discharge.  Repeat echo on day of discharge showed improving but still mildly diminished systolic function.  Repeat ECG at discharge showed persistent ST elevation. He was discharged with a prescription to continue ibuprofen 600 mg 3 times daily and follow-up with pediatric cardiology in 1 to 2 weeks.

Started vomiting 2hrs after vaccination. Went to ER who initially obtained CBC with stable Hgb and sent home with Zofran. Patient continued to have bloody emesis so presented back to ER where they did CXR which was normal, gave IVF bolus, zofran, repeat CBC with Hgb 12.4 and transferred to another hospital for higher level of care.  At the hospital, Initially made NPO and placed on IV fluids in preparation for possible endoscopy. Repeat labs showed stable hemoglobin compared to outside hospital. GI consulted and determined that hematemesis was most likely due to Mallory Weiss tear. Recommended carafate before meals, chloraseptic spray as needed for sore throat, continuing IV Protonix and IV zofran as needed, and gradually advancing her diet. On HD#3, she had another episode of hematemesis after eating solids. Overnight, tolerated liquids and solids without any further episodes of emesis. Tolerated transition from IV to PO meds and maintained hydration off of IV fluids. Due to symptom improvement, GI did not recommend endoscopy at this time and recommended that she be discharged on 1 week course of carafate, 2 month course of omperazole, and zofran as needed with plans for GI follow-up in 1-2 months. Had another episode of hematemesis at home after discharge. Went back to hospital and admitted again. The patient underwent upper endoscopy which showed no source of upper GI bleed. ENT was consulted and performed a nasopharyngolaryngoscopy which was negative for an ENT source of bleeding. She remained stable without an identifiable source of bleeding. Mom was comfortable with her being discharged home with close follow up by PCP. Pt seen on 6/7/21 at pediatrician's office for ER F/U. Pt reported she was still vomiting, 2x so far that day. The day before vomited 4x during the day and continued until the night. No more bright red blood in vomit. Describes vomit as blue and pink colors now. Pt does take a light green tablet that is her levothyroxine. Threw up the blue colored vomit immediately after taking this medication. Instructed to take zofran when feeling nauseous.   Seen again by pediatrician on 6/10/21- Currently, per mom pt is still vomiting. Last time she vomited was last night. Pt is taking omeprazole. Pt vomited 5-6x yesterday. Decreased appetite, but has been eating some crackers and rice. Complaining of stomach pain after eating and vomiting. Pt used zofran once and it helped a little. Pt denies self induced vomiting. Pt has ben observed by family when vomiting and they do not report any self induced vomiting. Pt denies trying to lose weight. Pt never vomits up food, always liquid. Vomit is different colors, can be pink or blue. No more red color in vomit, only pink. Pt drinks water and gatorade. Pt denies feeling any burning before vomit, but feels burning sensation after vomiting. Pt has been having BMs, not regularly and hard. Taking one capful of miralax at night.  Instructed for next five days, instructed to take zofran pill 1hr before dinner. F/U with GI.   Seen again by pediatrician on 6/15/21- Per mom and pt she is still vomiting about 5-6 times a day. Pt went to GI yesterday, given lansoprazole 30mg qd and told to continue zofran.. Pt is now able to eat all her meals, takes zofran 1hr before dinner. Pt has vomited 1hr after dinner and has only vomited liquids. Hematemesis has resolved. Still has some blue colored vomit, most likely from levothyroxine medication she takes daily. Stopped taking Miralax 3 days ago. Pt had a soft BM earlier this morning. Pt states she has occasional stomach pains after vomiting, takes a while to calm down but then resolves. Described as lower abdominal. Pt has nausea before vomiting, after vomiting takes 15-30mins for nausea to resolve. Pt states she had a headache with a heavy sensation when vomiting. No headaches at night, but does vomit 3-4x overnight. LMP: 2wks ago. Recommended to go to ophthalmologist to r/o papilledema. WIll contact hospital to get results of any bloodwork done inpatient (reviewed - only CBC done inpt).. F/U in 1wk. Ordered MRI brain w/contrast. CMP. lipase, amylase, celiac disease panel. All results pending.

The day after I received the vaccine I noticed that I had rashes on my left arm. It wasn't where I received the vaccine, but it was over my left hand. The next day, the rash started to spread to my other arm. Then it spread to both of my legs. It even spread to my buttocks. There was a little of a rash on my feet as well. I went and saw my PCP and she told me that it would just go away. I would have to wait for about 4 days for that. She said maybe a week or two at the most. It's not itchy. I noticed that it was still spreading so I went back to my doctor. I asked her if it could be a blood clot. She checked my blood and everything came back normal. I was worried because I was about to receive my 2nd dose. My doctor told me to see a dermatologist. It took me 1-2 months to get an appointment so I contacted an allergist. I went and he tested me for different allergies. He tested me on one of the ingredients of the vaccine. I was advised to take warm showers and stay away from the sun. I also saw a dermatologists assistant. I was prescribed a lotion/moisturizer. I was told to take Zinc and a drink called Juven. I still have the rashes all over my body. It's very prominent after I get out of the shower. I am going to see a dermatologist on 07/01. I really hope to get answers from this doctor.
LAB_DATA: I had blood work and a complete allergy test.
CUR_ILL: I was not experiencing any illnesses.
ALLERGIES: I do not have any allergies.

On 11/20/2020, patient did a blood test. The test results showed her abnormal numbers of TSH and T4 which was diagnosed as grave disease.  We then saw Dr. and he confirmed the grave disease. We then started the medication until today with a few blood tests along the treatment.  Patient's test results of TSH and T4 on Jan 14, 2019 before the HPV shot showed normal numbers.  We are very confident that the grave disease was caused by the HPV shots.
LAB_DATA: 1/12/2019 blood work before HPV shot showed normal 11/21/2020 blood work after the HPV shot showed grave disease

On 3/2 after receiving the 2nd dose I saw the optometrist again. They did different eye exams. Again ,they did not see anything wrong. He checked pupil dilation and noted that there was a slight delay in the left eye. Upon checking with HCP she said she did not notice any significant delay. I was able to have my vision compensated by my right eye. When my right eye vision became compromised. HCP ordered an MRI which showed a moderate to severe sinus infection and was prescribed antibiotics. The antibiotics did not help. On top of the antibiotics, I also took other medications for the sinusitis. I took the antibiotics from 4/14-4/21. After the antibiotics, on the 4/24 I noticed tingling and numbness on my face particularly from the tip of my nose to my chin and in circular area around my mouth. It is random and comes and goes through out the day, Also, on the same night of the numbness I experienced a bout of off balanced feeling and heaviness. It was a drunk feeling but I do not drink. I had 2 occurrences of this.  It went away in the morning I scheduled another appt because both my left and right eye were consistently blurry. The blurriness would get worse with movement and heat. After that appt she referred me to neurology and gave another dose of antibiotics. I took that from 4/19-4/25. Nothing changed after that round of antibiotics I went to the neurology appt on 6/9, they looked at the MRI and basically confirmed that nothing was wring neurologically. They said they did not have any explanation for the symptoms. My husband asked if there was a chance the vaccine could've caused it. They said they've seen some symptoms in patients but there is no way to confirm it was the vaccine.  I am still currently stuck with my loss of vision. It has prevented me from driving and doing any exercise. Many of the tasks I am able to do have been limited as well.

After I got my 1st COVID shot (Moderna April 6th), I started noticing my thumbs get numb and tingly (Hypoesthesia). At first I disregarded it because, a year ago, I had a mild spinal cord injury (requiring a neck brace). And after wearing the brace, I had a similar symptom that would flare up. So, when my thumbs did this, I figured, ?perhaps it?s my old injury just flaring up?? But, this time, the hypoesthesia began engulfing my pinky fingers too. I was obviously disturbed; but, I also figured it could simply be stress and carpal tunnel. This continued throughout the month in a mild way. After my 2nd COVID shot (May 4th), the tingly numbness spread to both heels and toes. And in the week following the vaccination, the numbness started to quickly shoot up both of my legs? all the way to the top of my butt cheeks. And finally, even my testicles started feeling tingly and numb.  It got to the point where I could barely handle sitting down for more than 10 minutes. My calf muscles also started to constantly twitch. So, with Guillain Barre Syndrome on my mind, I went into the E.R. They did a spinal tap and the labs came back normal. A month later, the symptoms slowly began to subside.
LAB_DATA: May 10th - Spinal Tap in ER to rule out Guillain Barre - Tests came back normal May 17th - I did blood tests to rule out Diabetes related neuropathy - Hypothyroid - Tests came back normal May 18th - I talked to my Rheumatologist to discuss possible side-effects with my TNF blockers (Cimzia) The following week, I talked to a Neurologist about the possibility that this numbness was related to my old neck injury.  But, as the numbness has slowly subsided, we concluded that it was an inflammatory response to the vaccine and not something more sinister.
OTHER_MEDS: Cimzia ? 200mg / once every 2 wks Prednisone ? 5mg/day Loratadine ? 10mg /day Lansoprazole ?15mg/day Methotrexate ? 15mg/wk Folic Acid ? 1mg/day Sertraline ? 50 mg/day
HISTORY: I've had Rheumatoid Arthritis - diagnosed in 2017. I also had a mild spinal injury / ligament strain in my neck in April 2020 (a year earlier).

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 4 days after vaccine dose, I started having pains that felt the same as when I was diagnosed with pericarditis prior. Pain under my left collar bone. It was mostly a sharp pain that was made much worse when taking a deep breath, or laying down. If I hadn't experienced this pain before, I may have gone to the emergency room. I was taking ibuprofen for the first week hoping that the pain would subside. I made a doctor appointment June 1 to be seen. The doctor didn't hear a pericardial rub, and prescribed Meloxicam for inflammation. At my 1 week follow up June 8, the pains had lessened, but were still present. The doctor gave me a prescription for Methylprednisolone, and after completing this round of steroids, the pain had gone away.
LAB_DATA: Doctor listened to heart for pericardial friction rub but didn't hear one. Doctor gave basic movement tests in arm to determine that it wasn't a pulled or strained muscle.
HISTORY: Had Pericarditis diagnosed December 2018 with AFIB. Follow ups have shown no recurrence since.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: SHE WAS GIVEN A WEEK EARLIER THAN HER EXPECTED DATE FOR HER SECOND SHOT

On Friday June 4th I visited a friend who informed me that she had just received the Pfizer vaccine. We hugged and spent several hours together during which I ate food that she prepared which included a raw carrot salad.  On Sunday June 6th at 1 pm, I noticed I felt very tired, which is unusual for me. At 4:15 I suddenly noticed a large bump inside my mouth on my right cheek near where my teeth come together.  I went to look in the mirror and saw a large deep purplish red blood blister that was the size and shape of half a marble. I popped it, the blood came out, but otherwise it did not seem to bleed. I put H202 on it, there was no pain. By about June 8th it had almost completely healed leaving only a slightly pinkish circle where it had been. Other than the fact that this was so much larger and so much more spherical than any blood blister I had ever had before (and it's been years since I did -- and they were ALWAYS the result of injuring my cheek -- which had not happened this time.) I didn't think much of it.  Then on Wednesday June 9th 4:08 pm, I suddenly noticed another large bump in the same general area.  I went to look in the mirror and saw another blood blister about the same size and shape of the first one -- but this one was slightly farther back and a tad lower in my mouth compared to the now slightly darker spot where the first one had been.  I popped this one and put H202 on it -- but a lot more blood came out of it -- at least a teaspoon and it just kept bleeding and bleeding. Then it bled several more times again over the next few days as well. It was also very painful. At first there was an inch long piece of loose skin hanging in my mouth -- but after two days, it had disappeared, but the pain continued on. There was a huge raw ulcer more than half an inch long and not quite as tall -- raw and red that would bleed from the slightest touch -- but it was completely flat, I could not feel any lump in my cheek from the inside nor the out. But unlike the first blister, this one just didn't seem to heal, so I started trying different things like gargling with salt water, and applying turmeric powder --- nothing seemed to help at all.  It was the amount of bleeding that caused me to connect this with my having been exposed to my just vaccinated friend -- as I had been hearing from so many others that they experienced prolific bleeding (from nose or vagina) after close contact with a just vaccinated person. And then the fact that this was so bizarre and not like any other event I have ever had. And also the fact that it just didn't seem to heal as fast injuries inside my mouth always have -- and did with the first blister.  It is now nearly a week since I first got the second blister. The circumference has shrunk to the size of a pea, but the middle is still as raw as ever and I am in constant pain, which is pretty alarming. I noticed on the trial protocol that it alludes to the fact that exposures to the vaccine can happen to people who did not get the injection but were exposed to the skin or breath of someone who did. That is what prompted me to file this report
OTHER_MEDS: T4. T3 Bacopa, Eleuthero, D3, K2, DHA/EPA, Methyl B-12

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This is most likely NOT related to the vaccine but it can't be ruled out so I wanted to be thorough.  Vaccine was on 4/9/21 and I had zero reactions, arm wasn't even sore really unless I poked at it.  Later, weekend of the 24-25th, I had a sunburn on the back of my neck, neosporin burn ointment was applied (and this may have caused the reaction but no one is sure).  Reaction was rash that slowly grew, covering areas under armpits, inner arms, sides and stomach.  Multiple trips to urgent care where they couldn't diagnose the issue and kept prescribing more steroids, antibiotics and antihistamines.  Finally was referred to allergy/dermatologist specialist,  biopsy was taken, results showed extremely high concentration of a certain kind of cell that indicates an allergic reaction - they were sure it's a reaction to some kind of medicine or medical treatment but were unable to positively identify whether it would have been the neosporin, the antibiotics, or some other thing.  My bet is that it's a neosporin reaction and not related to the vaccine.  I am only reporting this to be thorough, just in case.  The rash is now pretty much gone, with just some residual itchiness.
LAB_DATA: Biopsy performed on 5/26.  Results obtained on return visit to specialist on 6/9

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 6/14/21 This patient came in for her scheduled 4 month well child check and was due for vaccinations including Pediarix, HIB, rotateq and PCV13.  The vaccinations were administered to the patient with her mother present in the room at approximately 1135 by this RN.  After which the patient and her mother left the clinic. At approximately 1151, this RN went to document the vaccinations into the pts chart and discovered a medication error had occurred. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Please note patient did not receive vaccine at this organization.  Submitting  to VAERS following ED visit and admission.  23 y.o. male with no previous past medical history presented 6/10 with complaints of dizziness, presyncope and syncopal episodes.  Initial fainting episode was in January 2021 upon receiving sutures the laceration on his his right index finger.  At the time he reports that although he passed out he did not really lose consciousness as he was aware of his surroundings.  Things seem to go fine for a while until the day after he received his J &J vaccine in April 28, 2021.  Reports having the usual post vaccine symptoms such as myalgias and malaise but the following day  while at the barbershop he reports having another syncopal episode.  He reports a prodromal phase that includes shortness of breath, numbness of the lips and a generalized warm feeling.  During this episode he denied any loss of consciousness, as he was able to unlock his phone and respond to the people around him.  He denies any myoclonic movements or jerks.  He denies any postictal symptoms.  Patient has been seen in the ED 3 times within the last week.  On 6/10/2021 while at the base clinic, he reports feeling like he was about to pass out and was brought to the emergency department for further evaluation.  He denies any nausea, vomiting, headaches.  He endorses some chest pain when he lays down flat that is relieved by leaning forward.  He denies any recent illness.  Denies any new medications or changes to his diet or hydration status.    The day prior to admission, his ED visit for weakness and presyncope occurred shortly after PT eval at the base.  He felt very lightheaded and he attributes that to not eating and drinking prior to the PT eval.     Work-up in the ED included EKG which showed ST elevation in leads V3 and V4 in a biphasic pattern.  CT chest which showed no PE or consolidation pneumonia or pleural effusion.  CMP was remarkable for potassium of 3.4 serum bicarbonate of 21.  CBC was normal.  CK was slightly elevated at 913.  Troponin was negative.  Lactic acid was 1.9.  UA with no concern for infectious process.  UDS was negative.  Due to EKG findings reported above, patient was discussed with cardiologist who recommended that patient be admitted for observation.   Upon further discussion with patient, it was clear that his chest discomfort improved when leaning forward, and his EKG was consistent with diffuse ST elevation.  With a clinical diagnosis of acute idiopathic pericarditis, patient was initiated on colchicine 0.6 mg twice daily and ibuprofen 800 mg 3 times daily.  He is to continue his colchicine therapy for 3 months and his ibuprofen therapy for 1 to 2 weeks with a gradual de-escalation of that ibuprofen by 200 mg/week.  He has follow-up with cardiology scheduled.  Cardiology mentioned in their notes that they would obtain an echocardiogram to rule out structural heart disease and recommended a 2-week event monitor upon discharge with a 3-week follow-up with tilt table testing and exercise stress testing.  Cardiology had high suspicion for possible vasovagal.  Echocardiogram was unremarkable without pericardial effusion.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On April 1, 2021 the symptoms presented with right shoulder pain. Over the course of several days bilateral paralysis presented in the lower extremities.  On April 6, paralysis occurred in both hands/forearms. Then on April 7, bilateral facial paralysis was noted and was instructed to go to the local ER by PCP. A MRI of the brain and cervical region W/WO Contrast was performed along with spinal tap. On April 8, after a repeat MRI of the brain and cervical region, a diagnoses of Guillan Barre Syndrome was provided. April 8- April 12, 2021 IVIG therapy was administered while staying in the hospital. After the infusions were completed, I was moved to inpatient rehabilitation center on April 13. During my stay in the rehab unit I completed extensive therapy with OT/PT/SP along with neurophysiologist. I was discharged from hospital Rehab unit on April 22, 2021 (am). After discharge I was sent home and advised to continue outpatient therapy. I currently have paralysis in both legs, lower arms/hands, and right side of my face. I have been seeing a neruoopthamologist for my right eye as it can not close and is at risk for going blind. Currently I have not been given any sort of outcomes or time line as to when my condition should improve.
LAB_DATA: MRI brain W/WO Contract April 7  Spinal Tap April 8 **Guillan Barre Syndrome  Repeat MRI brain/cervical region April 8  Labs Draws April 7- April 22

Client received the COVID vaccine Janssen Lot#205A21A at 1:29 PM. RN was alerted by the client's family prior to vaccination that the client has a history of "fainting" with injections. RN recommended vaccination on the cot in the observation area to decrease risk of syncope. The client and his parents refused vaccination in the observation area and his mother stated "if he can look at his phone he'll be fine." The client received the vaccination at the table and ambulated to the observation area. RN was alerted by the client's parents at 1:39 and responded. EMT also responded at this time. The client was not verbally responsive to RN and EMT and his posture was tense sitting in the chair. RN elevated the client's legs on a metal chair. The client's posture relaxed and subsequently the client regained responsiveness. No injury was sustained. The client then stated that he was dizzy and lightheaded. He denied SOB, throat tightening, and itching. . Client was AOx4. Vitals obtained by EMT were as follows: BP 132/88 and HR 64 regular rate and rhythm. RN noted pallor on the client's face. At 1:42PM the client stated he was "a little bit dizzy" denied any other s/s of an allergic reaction. The client was offered water and began drinking it. No medications administered. Client denied any chronic conditions or medications and no known allergies. He began eating some goldfish at 1:45 PM. RN provided education to client and his parents regarding s/s of anaphylaxis, when to seek EMS, to follow up with PCP regarding syncope event, and V-safe. The client and his parents voiced understanding of this. Vitals obtained by EMT at 1:50 were BP 122/90, HR 72, RR 20. Repeat vitals obtained at 2:00PM were BP 122/86, HR 64, and RR 16. The client departed the vaccination site at 2:05 with his parents unassisted with a steady gait. The client's parents drove him home.
Vaccine Administration Error - administered vaccine underage. No adverse effects were noted following 15 minutes wait period.

The following is based on report from, Paramedic, (date of birth: 04/09/1993) received the 1st COVID vaccine (Pfizer, Lot #: ER8735 and expiration date: 07/31/2021) at 1309 on the left arm. Baseline vitals were obtained at 1332 by EMT while patient was sitting: blood pressure: 132/86, pulse: 91, respiratory rate: 16. Pupils were equal, accommodating, and reactive to light. Patient denied chest pain, shortness of breath, headache, blurry vision, and abdominal pain. Patient stated that the feelings of lightheadedness and nausea were improving. In addition, patient complained of left occipital/ neck pain. The pain was described as "sharp" and rated as a 2/10 on a pain scale. Bilateral pulses felt, motor sensation intact, and capillary refill was less than 3 seconds. Patient denied any reaction to the 1st COVID vaccine dose and denied any pertinent medical history. Patient claimed last oral intake was at 1030 when she had coffee and eggs. Patient was given water to sip on and an emesis bag. At 1338, chief complaint was reassessed. Patient claimed symptoms had resolved and denied any other complaints. Patient was conscious, alert, and oriented x4 and skins were noted to be improving in color and temperature. A second set of vital signs were taken at 1342 by EMT, while patient was standing: blood pressure: 129/84, pulse: 87, respiratory rate: 14. Pupils were equal, accommodating, and reactive to light. Patient was advised by Medic to sit for 10 more minutes. At 1350, patient stood up on her own. She advised Medic that she felt "much better." Medic educated the patient on when to contact their primary care physician with any other concerns and when to call 911, if symptoms warrant, or when to go to the ED. Patient then walked out of the site with a steady gait.

16 year old male with no PMH who presented with chest pain. Initially on 6/10-6/11 had expected myalgias and headaches post vaccination similar to dose #1, but later 6/11 developed chest pain that made it impossible for him to sleep. It was waxing and waning but continued through 6/12 which after discussion with PMD ultimately led to referral into our facility for further evaluation. Received a dose of ibuprofen with marked symptomatic relief. No further medications given during his time, his chest pain had resolved after that ibuprofen dose and was at clinical baseline until discharge on 6/15. Prolonged hospital course was to arrange for cardiac MRI to be done for comparison. Otherwise had serial labs (documented below) which had trended in the right direction.
LAB_DATA: 6/13/2021: CBC with differential (WBC 4.8, RBC 5.76, HgB 16.3, Hct 48.2, platelets 193, 42.4% neutrophils, 33.3% lymphocytes, 13.2% onocytes, 9.7% eosinophils, 1% basophils. 0.4% immature granulocytes) ESR 5,  CRP 51.27. BMP (sodium 141, potassium 4.4, chloride 108, Bicarb 21, BUN 7, Creatinin 0.81, Calcium 9.4, glucose 93).   6/13/21 early morning Cardiac Enzymes: Troponin I POC 2.76 ng/mL, CKMB 17.6 ng/mL, myoglobin >500ng/mL. 6/13/21 late morning Troponin I: 2.56ng/mL 6/14/21 troponin I: 1.35ng/mL  6/13 Respiratory viral panel: negative for Influenza A, Influenza B, RSV, Parainfluenza 1-4, Adenovirus, human metapneumovirus, and SARS-CoV-2.   6/13 SARS-CoV-2 IgG: <1.4 (negative) 6/13 Mycoplasma IgG: 1.30 (positive)  6/13 ASO: 146 unit/mL (normal) 6/13 Pending infectious disease tests: Anti-DNaseB titer, Coxsackie A titer, Coxsackie B titer, Mycoplasma IgM, Echovirus antibody  6/13 EKG: Sinus Rhythm with Sinus arrhythmia, Diffuse ST Elevation consistent with injury, pericarditis. 6/14 EKG: Sinus Rhythm with sinus arrhythmia   6/13 Echocardiogram: Structurally normal heart, normal appearing proximal coronary arteries (proximal LCA 3.9mm z -0.05; proximal RCA 3.6mm z 0.4), normal biventricular systolic function. no pericardial effusion.   6/15 cardiac MRI: HISTORY/REASON FOR STUDY: Patient is a 16-year-old boy with suspected vaccination induced myocarditis/pericarditis IMAGING SEQUENCES: Breath hold non-ECG gated 3-plane localizers; breath hold ECG gated 2,4 chamber and short axis ventricular SSFP imaging; Bright and block blood imaging across the chest; T1 myocardial imaging in the short axis pre- and post-contrast; early and delayed myocardial enhancement imaging 5 and 10-15 minutes following intravenous injection of Gadolinium. QUALITY/COMPLICATIONS: The patient was able to hold his breath throughout the study with no significant difficulty. The images are of adequate quality for interpretation. There were no complications related to the study.  FINDINGS: CARDIAC MRI STUDY with and without CONTRAST: There is levocardia, levoversion and {S,D,S} normal chamber/vessel interrelationships. Some pulmonary venous return to the left atrium is visualized. Systemic venous returns are normal to the right atrium. The cardiac septa appear intact. There is normal LV size with normal LV mass and no significant wall motion abnormality. The right ventricle is grossly normal in size and systolic function with no segmental wall motion abnormalities or free wall thinning. The cardiac valves appear grossly normal. The outflow tracts are patent. There are no obvious intracardiac masses. There is trace/small pericardial effusion.  There are no perfusion defects or areas of myocardial delayed enhancement. Myocardial T1 relaxation times are not abnormally increased.  SUMMARY: {S,D,S} normal anatomy. Normal LV function with no segmental wall motion abnormalities, perfusion defects, abnormally increased myocardial T1 relaxation time or areas of delayed myocardial enhancement. Trace/small pericardial effusion.
