The morning after I received the vaccine, I woke up and I had flu like symptoms. I had a low grade fever, some nausea, ringing in my ears and fatigue. By bedtime that night, I felt normal except for the tinnitus that stayed. I went to the doctor on 03/26, an audiologist, and she told me that it is tinnitus and she had another patient that got tinnitus after the vaccine also. I am having a lot of trouble hearing now. The doctor told me that the ringing that I hear is a short circuit in my brain. It's not so much in my ear, but from the processing of the brain. This is a habituation, which means I am listening to sounds through an app or web link to teach my brain how to ignore that sound. There is not any treatment for this condition. I will follow up with the doctor in a year.
LAB_DATA: I had an audio test performed.
OTHER_MEDS: I was taking melatonin and magnesium, both to help with sleep.
CUR_ILL: I did not have any other illnesses.
HISTORY: I do not have any chronic or long-standing health conditions.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received the 1st dose of the COVID vaccine (Pfizer Lot # ER8735 expiration date 07/05/2021) at 1547. At 1559, EMT noticed the client rubbing his arm in the location where he received the vaccine. EMT asked him how he was doing. The client stated that he was feeling "tingling at the injection site." PHN  and EMT assisted the client to the zero gravity chair at 1600. The client sated that he was not feeling any other symptoms but he has had similar reactions after receiving the flu vaccine, and stated, "my arm swells up, and gets stiff and it's hard to move." Client also stated, "I'm very afraid of needles." Skin around the injection site was the appropriate color to race and was free from erythema and discoloration. Vital signs were taken at 1601 (blood pressure 112/64, oxygen 96%, heart rate 88). Client stated at 1602, "I'm feeling hot now." Client removed his hat. PHN encouraged the client to drink his water, which he complied. PHN offered the client Benadryl at 1605, which he refused. At 1605, client stated, "I do not feel hot anymore." Client has no medical conditions, and is not taking any medications. Client stated that he has no known allergies other than the reaction to the flu vaccine. At 1611, client stated that the "tingling at the injection site was gone." Vital signs taken at 1611 (blood pressure 110/64, oxygen 97%, heart rate 88). Vital signs taken at 1621 (110/54, oxygen 97%, heart rate 80). Vital signs taken at 1629 (blood pressure 112/58, oxygen 97%, heart rate 75). Client stated at 1629, "I feel fine now." PHN provided education to the client on when to seek emergency services, and to follow up with his primary care provider and to see an allergist before receiving his second dose. Client left the facility at 1629, unassisted and with a steady gait.
ALLERGIES: Client stated that his arm swells, and becomes stiff after receiving the flu vaccine

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Right arm was sore very soon after shot, it was also painful to move completely around as it should. Into the evening I began to feel fatigued, and my muscles and joints started to ache. Into the night I began to get alternating chills/sweats and pain intensified in muscles and joints. I slept some, then woke up in terrible pain in wet clothes from the fever sweats. I took 800mg ibuprofen and slowly paced the hall like I was in labor until it kicked in. I was able to go back to bed, slept more. The next morning I was still very achey and feverish. Took another 800mg ibuprofen. Laid on couch and slept a lot! Continued chills & sweats throughout the day. Aches continued and right arm was swollen and painful. Diarrhea began 24-36 hours after shot. Continued to rest throughout evening. No appetite at all, just sipped on water.  Aches, pains continued into the night, but fever started to break. Nausea set it, along with headaches. Took another 800mg ibuprofen. Slept some more, but was restless. Woke up on third day and vomitted twice in the morning. Aches and pains subsided, fever wore off, but I was wiped out for a good 4-5 days. This was a much stronger reaction than the first dose, and I was not expecting to feel so terrible. My husband asked me a couple times if I needed to go to hospital the first night after shot. It was pretty rough.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Commencing approximately 18 hours after the vaccination (which was my second Pfizer vaccine), I developed a rash that started under my arms and on my lower abdomen.  Within approximately 4 hours the rash had spread across my chest, up my neck to the chin, around my waist and up the center of my back, and down the insides of my arms.  The rash remained inflamed and red, and the skin sensitive, for approximately 72 hours before it began to fade.  Within 5 days of beginning, the rash had subsided completely.
LAB_DATA: I did not seek medical treatment at the time; I consulted a physician some weeks later.  I have experienced similar but less severe rash reactions in the past that appeared to be caused by ingestion of certain drugs (e.g., ibuprofen).  When the rash broke out following the vaccination, I responded by taking Benadryl tablets, though it did have any noticeable effect or diminish the rash.  I also monitored the rash to see if it would become more severe or spread to parts of my body that have never been affected in the past.  Ultimately, although the inflammation of the skin was more extensive than I have ever seen it, I did not believe that I needed to seek emergency medical treatment.  I consulted my allergist on June 16, 2021, and he recommended that I file a report with VAERS.
OTHER_MEDS: Tylenol - 500 mg tablets: took one in the evening after the vaccine and one the following morning at about 6 am

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I notified by Dr. that after receiving the Shingles vaccine, I had a severe reaction of weakness in my legs that lasted about 2 months and was afraid to get the 2nd dose.  He said the reaction was rare and the CDC recommended to get the 2nd dose. I got the 2nd dose on 2/22/21 and by the next day, the reaction of weakness was SEVERE and has continued to get worse. I have a very difficult time walking and have a bad gait with foot drop. I fall a lot and it is impossible to stand up or climb stairs without assistance. I have to use a wheelchair often. Now after 3 months, I've sought help from a Neurologist and now under his care and testing. (Dr.).  Both doctors said they are not aware of any connection to the Shingles vaccine. However, I was a very healthy person and immediately after both doses of the vaccine, the severe leg weakness occurred. I never would have gotten the 2nd dose if I was informed that the side effect could be even worse and long-term.  My life has changed dramatically.  As of this date, I have undergone four MRI's and have given 12 vials of blood for about 20 blood tests.  Dr. is trying to figure out the exact diagnosis and treatment.  The Nerve Conduction test showed that a major nerve in both legs in non-functioning.  The CK blood test is flagged with an extremely high number.   I now understand that Guillain-Barre Syndrome is a possibility.  I don't believe either of my doctors are aware of this effect as they didn't think there was any connection to the vaccine.   I am writing this VAERS form to inform more doctors and the vaccine maker of this possible long-term side effect if nerve damage and leg weakness.

Around 04/30/2021 I ended up getting some facial paralysis, a pretty quick onset on the left side of my face. I started to notice I had some difficulty shutting my eye. I wasn't having any slurred speech. I recognized it as a possible Bells Palsy because I have coworkers that have it. My eye sight started to become more affected. I went to the ER that same day to rule out stroke. They ran blood tests and CT scan to rule out any signs of stroke. Everything came back negative and they found no cause for paralysis and assumed it was bells palsy. . I was put on prednisone and an anti-viral drug Baclamir (something that started with B ) . I was on about a weeks worth of the anti viral and about 10 days of the prednisone, and the first 8 days I was showing signs of improvement .  I couldn't shut my left eye, raise my eyebrow, my whole face was numb on L side and I lost taste on L side of tongue. They did test me for Covid when I went to ER. I had a metallic taste in my mouth. I took medicine and recovered quickly but within 3-7 days, I ended up getting a rash on my back but it wasn't a regular rash because it didn't itch. It was the worst back acne possible, around 200 bumps on back that erupted overnight. The ER did r/o shingles but this rash was on several different nerve paths, it looked more like a reaction to the prednisone. I am an Archeologist and they ran a test to see if I had lyme disease because I come across ticks regularly but they came back negative for current and past infection.  When I take Amoxicillin I do get heart palpitations and that's why I was on the doxycycline. I do take testosterone 1 shot a month in the hip. On the 8th day around 05/08/2021  it started to improve and every day after that was a 5% improvement.

Patient complained of feeling unwell and having headaches after his second dose of Moderna vaccine on 2/2/2021. He became increasingly confused, paranoid and started occasionally refusing medications. On early March 2021, he started refusing all medications.  Around 3/17/21, his increasing confusion and paranoia prompted suspicion for UTI which was confirmed with a urinalsis. Unfortunately, he refused antibiotic treatment. On 3/20/2021, nursing staff noted that patients right lower extremity was purple from toes to mid-calf, cold to touch and pedal pulse were not present. He complained of right leg pain. He was evaluated and diagnosed with probable thromboembolic event, since patient refused his oral anticoagulant for weeks prior to these event. Patient was sent to the local Emergency Department (ED) and diagnosed with acute critical right limb ischemia. At the local ED, he had a CTA which showed as per radiology: "Occlusion of the right superficial femoral artery beginning just beyond the origin. Occluded right popliteal, anterior tibial, tibioperoneal, peroneal, and posterior tibial arteries without reconstitution on arterial and delayed phases. Patent right deep femoral artery with minimal luminal stenosis in the proximal segment. Patent mid and distal right external iliac artery with up to mild luminal stenosis."  Per discharge summary, "vascular surgery evaluated patient in the ED and did not feel operative revascularization with fasciotomy would provide any benefit; recommended continued anticoagulation with amputation/palliative management." He was admitted to the general medicine service which consulted orthopedic, infectious diseases and palliative care. Medicine Service also contacted patient's daughter who is his next of kin who opted for comfort care. He was discharged to facility on 3/25/2021 and started in the Comfort Care Program. He was pronounced dead on March 27, 2021 at 0807 hours.  His autopsy showed that he also had thrombi on: 1. Pulmonary embolism, Left pulmonary artery 2. Left renal infarct

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Notes in record state Shingrix given 5/4/21 left arm SQ.  This is an employee so I was able to talk with her face to face on 6/14/21.  Patient showed me the injection site which was on the lateral aspect of the left upper arm between the bicep and the tricep, well below the deltoid: typically where subcutaneous injections are given.  Patient complained of pain, redness and swelling that lasted a couple of weeks.  She drew a circle on her arm with her finger illustrating the area of redness, which was approximately 5 inches in diameter.  She is concerned about what she calls a ?shadow? circle about 1.5 inches in diameter that is still lingering and wonders if it will ever go away.  I noticed a faint circular discoloration when she pointed it out and suggested she discuss with her provider. She also reported feeling sick all over from the shot.  I told patient that it looks like the shot might have been given subcutaneous.  I asked if this was her first shot for shingles, and she said it was the first, and she is really reluctant to get the second after this reaction.  She asked if it might be less severe this time, and I told her I could not say for sure, but it would be a good idea to discuss this with her doctor and get all her questions answered so she could make an informed decision about the 2nd shot.  She agreed that would be a good idea.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: patient had denied having any other corona virus vaccine while access to state immunization records was down and later discovered she already received a dose

I called the patient and spoke with her on the phone on 6/14/21.  I asked if she remembered getting a shot for shingles on 6/1/21.  She did remember and reported that her arm got red and swollen and painful, that the swelling took up most of her arm and lasted for a couple of weeks.  She also reported feeling sick all over from the shot.  She was miserable she said, and reported not understanding what the shot was for, she at first thought it was for a bone spur in her heel.  Now she knows it was for shingles and asked about shingles.  I provided some education on shingles.  I explained that the reason I was calling was it came to  our attention that there might have been an error in how the shot was given, or a documentation error, and I needed her help to figure it out.  I asked her to describe where the shot was given.  She stated it was given in her right arm, straight down from the clip in her bra strap.  She could not clarify if it was down from the tip of her shoulder, but said it was about a hand width, or maybe 3 or fingers down from the clip in her bra strap.  I asked if it was in the back of her arm and she said not really, more in the middle.  I told her it may have been given in a muscle or in the subcutaneous or fatty part of her arm, I could not tell from her story.  She could not clarify.  I explained that it is best if this shot goes in a muscle, but if it goes into the subcutaneous tissue, it is still effective, so it would not have to be repeated.  I asked if this shot was her first shot for shingles, and she said yes.  I told her she only needed one more.  Patient said there was no way she was going to get the second shot after the misery this one caused. I expressed empathy for her ordeal, and invited her to discuss the pros and cons of the second shot with her provider.
OTHER_MEDS: aspirin, vit c, duloxetine, vit D, insulin, HCTZ, metformin, gabapentin, nitroglycerin, semaglutide, lisinopril, carvedilol

SYMPTOM_TEXT: First received my 1st dose of Moderna Vaccine for Covid-19 on 01/15/2021 with slight headache few hours after vaccination, which I treated with counter the counter pain reliever. Second dose was on 02/21, with body chills and headaches that lasted 3 days. From waist up I also experienced upper body aches and soreness for 4 days, treated with over the counter pain reliever, symptoms were stubborn but went away after 4 days.  2 weeks later experienced chills between my right hips, that last about a week. Fast forward to 2 weeks at the ending of April 2021, I have been experiencing pains and aches in my heart, right on the left side of my chest. The pain, aches are heavy and tight, sometimes it last all day none stop like yesterday and today, most of the time it keeps me up all night, very achy, heavy and uncomfortable to sleep. Sometimes I wake up with the same pain. It has causes shortness of breath for me,  fast heart beats and flutters with no reasonable explanation other than the Modern Covid-19 vaccine I took in 02/2021. I have never experienced anything like this in my entire life, was not sick before the vaccination either.  Went to the Emergency room last week, and currently waiting on my cardiologist appointment which I was referred to by the attending ER medical doctor.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 6/16/21 patient received her first shot of Moderna  RX  7800192  that as administered my Registered Pharmacy Technician.  At 5:58 pm she received the immunization.  Within about 2 minutes her boyfriend, alerted us that patient was not feeling well.  It was then that I, went to the patient to see how she was doing.  At this time patient was very week, she said she felt hot, tied, felt nausea. I then had pharmacy technician to assist me  (with note taking)with the patient .  Brought out our immunization cart to assist with the needs of the patient.   At this moment we called a Code White for store management to call for an ambulance, notified our market manager.  I applied a cold compress on patient's back and a wet compress for her forehead to help with the flushing she was experiencing.  She was responsive but very weak.  She was so week that she was not able to move at the time, so she remained in a chair and laid her head down.  As she was doing this I continued with the cold compress (back and head) and asked if her breathing was ok.  She continued to say yes. No Epi-Pen was needed at this time.   Blood Pressure at 6:05 was 116/88  HR 65.  Blood pressure was taken again about 5 minutes later 121/71  HR  66.    Her boyfriend who was with her provided us with a history and said in the past she has been dizzy from shots before.  But it has not been this bad.    I continued to stay with the patient and asked about her breathing of which she said she was ok.  She continued to say she just felt very weak.  I continued with the cold compress (head and back) to help with temperature of which she said was helpful.  I continued to console patient to let her know that she was ok.     I asked her if she was breathing ok or had any tightness in her chest.  She responded that her breathing was ok.  I told her I was going to continue to ask her as we were waiting for the ambulance to arrive.    An ambulance arrived at 6:17pm and assess the patient.  Pharmacy technician provided the paramedics with the shot and Lot number:  Moderna and lot number provided.   Paramedics convinced patient to go to the ER with them.  I told her it was just precautionary to make sure she would be ok.  Patient agreed.    I then proceed to get a phone number from boyfriend and told him we would like to call in a day or 2 to make sure she is ok.  He said thank you.  We will follow up with boyfriend to check on patient in a few days.
LAB_DATA: unknown  patient was taken to local hospital ER

Patient received IM Pfizer dose in Left arm at 4:10pm and moved to the waiting area.  About 5-10 min later she had developed a red, slightly raised blotch area around the injection site and down her left arm.  She said it did not itch, but felt warm and slight burning feeling.  Patient complained of being hot and nervous, but breathing was normal no chest tightness.  We had her get up and go outside (with 2 nursing staff members) to see if fresh air and no mask would help calm her.  On coming back in, the rash was still present and a small patch developed on her other arm.  WE gave her a cold compress and measured out 75mg of liquid diphenhydramine. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Client received his first COVID19 Pfizer dose (Lot #EW0187 Exp:  08/31/21) on 06/15/21 at 1654.  Client was accompanied by a friend and after receiving the injection they were instructed by RN1 to sit in the observation room for 15 minutes.  At approximately 1710 client was sitting in a chair in the observation room and informed RN2 and EMT that he felt dizzy.  RN2 and EMT opened the zero-gravity chair for client to sit in and client was able to transfer himself into it.  EMT also gave client a bottle of water and he took a few sips.  Client reclined in the zero-gravity chair and EMT took his vitals at 1722 (BP:  160/104, HR:  102, O2Sat:  97).  RN2observed that client was alert and oriented to time, place, event & self and did not exhibit any cognitive impairment.  Client informed EMT and RN2 that he did not have any shortness of breath or trouble breathing.  Client also stated that he has a history of high blood pressure and fibromyalgia.  Additionally, client stated he was currently chewing nicotine gum because he had quit smoking two weeks prior.  EMT obtained vitals at 1731 (BP:  155/100, HR: 112, O2Sat: 97).  Client stated he was feeling a little better.  EMT took vitals at 1736 (BP:  151/102, HR: 109, O2Sat: 97).  Client stated he had eaten and drank plenty prior to getting vaccinated.  EMT took client?s vitals again (BP:  141/101, HR: 94, O2Sat: 97).  At 1755 client informed RN2 and EMT that he felt fine and was leaving.  EMT and RN2 observed client was using a walker and could stand just fine.  RN2 informed client that he should go to urgent care if he began to experience any dizziness and/or his blood pressure continued to exceed recommended guidelines. RN2 also recommended client monitor his blood pressure and seek medical attention if he began to experience any shortness of breath, trouble breathing, or chest pain.  Client and his friend then left the observation room.  EMT went to the Lead room at 1758 and informed Lead RN of the incident that just occurred with the client.  Lead RN reviewed details with EMT and determined that EMT and RN2 had not obtained a complete medical history on the client, determined what medications he was taking, and/or if he had any known allergies.  Lead RN immediately walked to the observation room with EMT and informed both he and RN2 of the proper protocol for follow if a client has a reaction to a vaccine.  Lead RN noted that while RN2 and EMT adequately monitored the client and documented their actions, they did not obtain all necessary information or notify a Lead or Co-Lead RN of the situation as it was occurring.  EMT and RN2 communicated that they now understand what the proper protocol is and will ensure that it is followed if future incidents occur.

At 4:15pm client reports sweatiness is resolving and PHN check rash and does not observe any spread.  Client reports it is not itchy and is not having any difficult swallowing or breathing.  At 4:18pm vitals: blood pressure:140/90, pulse:78, and oxygen:97%.  Client reports no chest pain, no shortness of breath, no dizziness, no difficulty breathing, no blurred vision,  and no headache. Client is alert and oriented x 4.  At 4:21pm client reports sweating has completely resolved. At 4:23pm vitals: blood pressure:140/90, pulse:83, and oxygen:98%.  Client reports no symptoms. At 4:30pm vitals: blood pressure 138/92, pulse:83, and oxygen:97%. Client reports no chest pain, no headache, no trouble breathing, no other symptoms. At 4:35pm, vitals: blood pressure:148/98 and pulse:80 and oxygen: 98%. No symptoms reported, assessed for hypertensive crisis.  At 4:42pm,reassess blood pressure:150/90 and client reports no shortness of breath, no chest pain. PHN provided ER precautions and advised client see PCP about rash. Client completed 30 minute observation and rash still noted on chest and neck. Client reports no difficulty breathing and that she "feels fine to drive."  Client left facility at 4:46pm walking out with a steady gait, unassisted.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: At 1259 client aged 19yo, was vaccinated in her left arm with the Janssen vaccine lot#205A21A.  At 1306 client  requested a bottle of water as she reported feeling dizzy.  Vaccine monitor brought a bottle of water to vaccination room and immediately observed client's eyes begin to lose focus, so client was supported as she fainted, and placed safely on the floor with her legs elevated her legs on a chair and within seconds she regained consciousness. RN conducted a neuro-check on client and confirmed client was AxO x4.  The zero gravity chair was retrieved and EMT summoned, and at 1310 client was assisted to her feet by Co-Lead RN and RN and transferred to this chair.  At 1311 water was offered to client and she took a few sips and admitted she felt a lot better.  At 1312 EMT took client's first set of vitals which were: BP 110/70, HR 60, RR18, and O2 98%.  Co-lead confirmed with Vaccinator that client had been appropriately screened, that client had denied past syncopal episodes and had ate food today at 1000.   At 1314, Co-Lead RN asked client again if she had ever experienced syncope, and she admitted that she had once when visiting her uncle in the hospital. Co-Lead then educated client that it is not uncommon to faint due to anxiety related to medical procedures and encouraged her to report this to her physician and to any medical personnel in the future during medical procedures so proper safety precautions can be engaged.  Co-Lead then applied a cold pack to the back of client's neck, and EMT took a second set of vitals: BP 120/70, HR 63, O2 100%.  Client remained in the vaccination room 1328 when she felt well enough to walk to the observation room escorted by EMT to complete a 30 minute observation period.  At 1339 when EMT approached client to take her vitals again, client stated she was dizzy again, so EMT requested she remain for another 15 minutes and have a snack.  At 1400, client stated she felt better, her vitals were taken for the last time by the EMT: BP 110/60, HR 56, O2 98%, and EMT then escorted client downstairs where her mother was waiting with the car.  EMT and Co-Lead RN educated client to take it easy for the rest of the day and seek additional care with her PCP or Urgent Care if symptoms worsened.  EMT observed client ambulating independently with a steady, even gait.

There he had a normal ECG and chest x-ray. He was referred to see me in clinic on 6/15/2021. He had a normal echocardiogram. Due to the parental concern for possible myocarditis, I recommended a troponin which would show if his chest pain were possibly related to that. It returned mildly elevated at 0.21 ng/mL, prompting me to enter this as a possible mild case of myocarditis after vaccination.
LAB_DATA: 6/15/2021 at 12:22 Troponin-I 0.21 ng/mL 6/15/2021 ECG: Normal sinus rhythm, normal ECG. 6/15/2021 Echo: Normal echocardiogram, LVEF 64.5%

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 2 weeks after the shot I had a scary night where I had severe chest pain. I sat up for a few hours hoping I wasn't having a heart attack and taking water and tums. I have never had chest pain before or since. I was very concerned and wondered if it was the vaccine. I didn't have anything unusual to eat or drink. I was happy when it finally resolved that same night.  I also experienced Bell's Palsy 2 months after the vaccine. (~June 1st) I have never experienced Bell's Palsy. I am not sure if either of these events were related to the vaccine, but I have no intention of getting a yearly covid or flu vaccine now that I have Bell's Palsy. It is terrible, and I'm not taking ANY chance of getting this again even if that means I get the flu and covid yearly. I placed my trust in science, and not I am not sure I made the right choice. Although I hope my facial movement and ability to use my lips and face come back, I realize that some never recover.
LAB_DATA: Emergency room visit June 2nd, 2021 for Bell's Palsy

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Lips went totally white and chapped, burning all around my lips began (day after shot) Burning got worse the next day around my mouth, lips got even more chapped (two days after) Ate something I've never reacted to before for dinner after dinner my entire face broke out in rash, my lips swelled up, my throat swelled, blood pressure dropped, heart raced, and I was about to faint (so lay down). Stopped reaction with two benedryl.  (three days later) - note this sort of thing has happened before after certain drugs when taken in aggregate over days (Malarone, Gabapentin)   For next 4 weeks I had a host of symptoms that were unliveable including (note: some have lasted longer) - Fainting spells, low blood pressure - Full body nerve pain and facial nerve pains that were very intense  - Dry mouth - Tachycardia at night (RAPID heart beat) - Lip angioedema usually in the morning only to be controlled with antihsitimines (still the case months later) - Massive diarrhea usually in the morning with lip angiodema   - Trouble breathing and chest pain and wheezing, one massive asthma attack  Treatment:   Antihistimines at first, but made POTS too bad so went off (helped swelling though) Steroid inhaler to help me breath  Steroids (prednisone) burst in late April/early May - moderately helpful when on the course, but made digestive issues worse and acid reflux worse, lip burning and swelling came back after i went off this  Post-Steroid burst: - Still having lip burning - Still having horrible dry mouth - Still trouble breathing and wheezing and shortness of breath - horrible digestive issues (acid reflux) - nerve pain   Treatment post steroids  - treated my MCAS  - Quercetin, Vitamin C, and NAC, eventually found compounded allegra to work without the dysautonomia side effects and now on 180mg / day has helped a lot of these symptoms - Using Cromolyn  Sodium nebulized for the breathing issues and chest pain - helping a lot for this!  With the MCAS drugs I'm improved, but I still have the following (June 16) - horrible acid reflux all day every day (doesn't matter what I eat) - Dry mouth  - I also have lip burning that is pretty constant (although swelling is down) - Moderate wheezing (but its better than before) - Moderate facial pain (but better than before) - Headaches (pretty sure it's a side effect of my meds)
LAB_DATA: Chest X Ray (sometime in April) Asthma Breath test - blow into a tube (not normal, but don't remember what it was) Pulmanary functioning testing (getting tomorrow 6/16)   Lots and Lots of labs - please contact my doctor, Vitamin D low is about all that came back abnormal
OTHER_MEDS: I took an allegra 20 mg about an hour prior to vaccination
CUR_ILL: None. My chronic condition was very much under control at time of vaccination.
HISTORY: I have Mast Cell Activation Syndrom (MCAS) and have for years since I had a viral infection when in another country in my early 20s, I was left with MCAS basically after that infection. At the time of vaccination my MCAS was very under control and not in a flair. I was feeling pretty healthy actually. I also had been diagnosed with POTS previously, but was very rarely symptomatic.
ALLERGIES: I am allergic to Malarone, Gabapentin, Amatriptyline, also allergic to gluten and dairy. I have Mast Cell Activation Syndrom and am a fairly allergic person in general do to this condition.

Herpes zoster; This initial spontaneous report was received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation and refers to a female patient of unspecified age. No information was provided regarding medical history, concurrent conditions, or concomitant medications. On an unknown date, the patient was inoculated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (lot number, dosage and route of administration not provided) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster). After receiving zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient suffered herpes zoster. As a result of these symptoms, the patient was seen and treated by medical providers and was still under their care. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient's symptoms had resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX). The patient also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of the patient's condition. As a result of the manufacture, marketing, advertising, promotion, distribution and/or sale of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. Further, as a tragic consequence of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient had suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages. The outcome of the event was considered not recovered/not resolved. The event was considered related to zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX).  The event of herpes zoster was considered as disability.
